/*Program to demonstrate Function, Passing Arguments to a Function
(call by value and call by reference) */
// Name - ____
// Roll No - _____

Function:
A function is a block of code that performs a specific task. It can take inputs (parameters)
and return a value.
Call by Value:
In call by value, the actual value of the argument is passed to the function.
Changes made to the parameter inside the function do not affect the actual value.
In the second example, the swap function swaps the values of a and b inside the function,
but the original values of x and y in main remain unchanged.
Call by Reference:
In call by reference, the address of the argument is passed to the function.
Changes made to the parameter inside the function affect the actual value.
In the third example, the swap function swaps the values of a and b using their addresses,
so the original values of x and y in main are swapped.



#include <stdio.h>
// Function declaration
void swapByValue(int a, int b);
int main() {
int x = 10, y = 20;
printf("Before swapByValue: x = %d, y = %d\n", x, y);
swapByValue(x, y);
printf("After swapByValue: x = %d, y = %d\n", x, y);
return 0;
}
// Function definition
void swapByValue(int a, int b) {
int temp = a;
a = b;
b = temp;
printf("Inside swapByValue: a = %d, b = %d\n", a, b);
}
